---
import { Picture } from 'astro:assets';
import darkroom from '../assets/darkroom.png';
---

<section class="ritual" id="ritual">
  <div class="ritual-header">
    <div class="section-label reveal">The Ritual</div>
    <h2 class="section-heading center reveal reveal-heading" style="--reveal-delay: 80ms">Film. Light. Paper. Retouch.</h2>
    <p class="section-body reveal" style="margin: 0 auto; --reveal-delay: 160ms">
      Four stages, in the order a photograph is actually made. Source.
      Interpretation. Realization. Mend.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="ritual-stages">

    <div class="stage">
      <div class="stage-text">
        <div class="stage-marker reveal">Stage One · Origin</div>
        <h3 class="stage-name reveal reveal-heading" style="--reveal-delay: 80ms">Film</h3>
        <div class="stage-subtitle reveal" style="--reveal-delay: 160ms">Choose where the photograph comes from.</div>
        <p class="stage-body reveal" style="--reveal-delay: 240ms">
          Start in Pure RAW — your file as the camera saw it — or in Origin,
          Latent's own signature blend. Then put it through emulsion:
          thirty-seven film stocks, five chemistries (C-41, ECN-2, E-6, K-14,
          B&amp;W), five scanners. The negative develops, the enlarger prints,
          the paper holds the image. Halation, grain physics, push and pull,
          and a latitude indicator that reads from the stock you chose.
          Nothing is a filter.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="stage-image reveal" style="--reveal-delay: 320ms">
        <Picture
          src={darkroom}
          formats={['avif', 'webp']}
          widths={[480, 800, 1200, 1600]}
          sizes="(min-width: 900px) 800px, 100vw"
          alt="Film stage — stocks, chemistry, scanner, paper"
          loading="lazy"
        />
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="stage">
      <div class="stage-text">
        <div class="stage-marker reveal">Stage Two · Interpret</div>
        <h3 class="stage-name reveal reveal-heading" style="--reveal-delay: 80ms">Light</h3>
        <div class="stage-subtitle reveal" style="--reveal-delay: 160ms">Bring the image forward.</div>
        <p class="stage-body reveal" style="--reveal-delay: 240ms">
          Exposure, the four lights — Highlights, Shadows, Whites, Blacks —
          and a tone curve with L, R, G, B channels and a live histogram.
          Then Structure: Depth for how forms separate, Surface for the
          texture of skin and stone and fabric. Then Dye Density, four
          sliders that handle color the way film does — Intensity, Retention,
          Separation, Purity — never as a single saturation knob. Finally
          Color, an eight-channel densitometer plate over a rainbow strip.
          None of it as zones. Everything as a continuous field.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="stage-image reveal" style="--reveal-delay: 320ms">
        <img src="/images/workbench.png" alt="Light stage — tone, dye density, color spectrum" />
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="stage">
      <div class="stage-text">
        <div class="stage-marker reveal">Stage Three · Realize</div>
        <h3 class="stage-name reveal reveal-heading" style="--reveal-delay: 80ms">Paper</h3>
        <div class="stage-subtitle reveal" style="--reveal-delay: 160ms">Finish on a surface.</div>
        <p class="stage-body reveal" style="--reveal-delay: 240ms">
          The Enlarger sets paper grade, contrast, and density. The Paper has
          its own base and finish, with control over how the print lands into
          its blacks. The Wash is a split-tone that warms or cools shadows,
          midtones, and highlights independently — a real darkroom toner, not
          a filter. The Fall-Off burns light at the edges of the frame the way
          an enlarger naturally would. Texture lays a plate of real film grain
          — 35mm, 16mm, 500T, 8mm — across the print. A Gallery Finish frame,
          if you want one. Then Deliver: Quick Export, or Export Catalogue for
          the full batch.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="stage-image reveal" style="--reveal-delay: 320ms">
        <img src="/images/lighttable.png" alt="Paper stage — enlarger, wash, fall-off, finish" />
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="stage">
      <div class="stage-text">
        <div class="stage-marker reveal">Stage Four · Mend</div>
        <h3 class="stage-name reveal reveal-heading" style="--reveal-delay: 80ms">Retouch</h3>
        <div class="stage-subtitle reveal" style="--reveal-delay: 160ms">The polishing pass.</div>
        <p class="stage-body reveal" style="--reveal-delay: 240ms">
          Spotting brush. Clone stroke. The work you would otherwise leave the
          app for. After the print is realized, this is where the dust is
          removed, the small distractions tidied, the photograph made ready.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="stage-image reveal" style="--reveal-delay: 320ms">
        <img src="/images/studio.png" alt="Retouch stage — spotting and clone" />
      </div>
    </div>

  </div>
</section>

